When importing in a cloud instance a Server instance backup with Portfolio for Jira 2.6.0 or above, the import fails in some cases with error:
{code:java}
com.atlassian.rdbms.dbimportexport.runner.api.ImportExportException: Failed to import sequence data for AO_D9132D_ASSIGNMENT_EXT belonging to com.atlassian.jpo
{code}
This is due to the scenario column not expecting null values in Portfolio for Jira cloud.

 

*Workaround:*

Remove the rows that have a null value before doing the export
{code:java}
DELETE FROM "AO_D9132D_ASSIGNMENT"
WHERE "SCENARIO" IS NULL;

DELETE FROM "AO_D9132D_ASSIGNMENT_EXT"
WHERE "SCENARIO" IS NULL;

DELETE FROM "AO_D9132D_SOLUTION"
WHERE "SCENARIO" IS NULL;
{code}
Note: Those tables contain data related to plan and program calculation and removing those rows will not result in a data loss

h3. Summary
Example scenario:
# Hierarchy levels:
#* Program - Program issue type
#* Initiative - Initiative issue type
#* Epic - Epic issue type
#* Story - Story issue type

After moving an Initiative to Program issue type, the [Issue Property|https://docs.atlassian.com/jira/REST/server/#api/2/issue/\{issueIdOrKey}/properties] still intact.

h3. Steps to Reproduce
# Step up the Hierarchy levels as above.
# Create an issue with Program issue type.
# Create an issue with Initiative issue type.
# Set the Initiative issue's Parent link to Program issue.
# Move Initiative issue to change the issue type to Program issue type.

h3. Expected Results
Checking the originally created Program issue:
# {{<Base URL>/rest/api/2/issue/<Issue key>/properties/}}
*Result*:
{code}
{"keys":[{"self":"<Base URL>/rest/api/2/issue/10013/properties/sd.initial.field.set","key":"sd.initial.field.set"}]}
{code}
# Hacking the request from the Actual Result to check {{jpo-issue-properties}}:
{{<Base URL>/rest/api/2/issue/10013/properties/jpo-issue-properties}}
*Result*:
{code}
{"errorMessages":["The property jpo-issue-properties does not exist."],"errors":{}}
{code}

h3. Actual Results
# {{<Base URL>/rest/api/2/issue/<Issue key>/properties/}}:
*Result*:
{code}
{"keys":[{"self":"<Base URL>/rest/api/2/issue/10015/properties/jpo-issue-properties","key":"jpo-issue-properties"},{"self":"<Base URL>/rest/api/2/issue/10015/properties/sd.initial.field.set","key":"sd.initial.field.set"}]}
{code}
# {{<Base URL>/rest/api/2/issue/10015/properties/jpo-issue-properties}}:
*Result*
{code}
{"key":"jpo-issue-properties","value":{"parent_id":"10013"}}
{code}

h3. Notes
# The Parent link information on the issue itself shows up fine and does not have any link to the old Parent after changing the issue type. 
# Parent Link JQL also returns the correct result.

h3.Workaround
You can delete the Issue Property by using this REST API; [DELETE /rest/api/2/issue/\{issueIdOrKey}/properties/\{propertyKey}|https://docs.atlassian.com/jira/REST/server/#api/2/issue/\{issueIdOrKey}/properties-deleteProperty].

As a product owner, I need to be able to get a view of team health over time in terms of committed stories vs completed stories to see how we are trending and to make decisions for future plans. Surfacing information that may only currently be visible on the Team scrum boards in some fashion in Portfolio to facilitate retrospectives from a multi-team product view would be very helpful.

To know if there was over/under commitment for a sprint or release. {color:#373737}This metric is used to measure the development team’s ability to know and understand their capabilities. To compare the number of stories committed to in sprint planning and the number of stories identified in the sprint review as completed. {color}

e.g Agile team-level reports across multiple teams in a plan - Cross team burn-down, burn-up etc.
